    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Printing Photos at Home</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Jim Jondrow on June 15 article on home-printed snapshots; says computer-printed pictures should not be compared in price with drugstore prints and are more in the class of home-darkroom prints</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Snapshots printed at home may be pricey, but I don't think computer-printed pictures should be compared in price with drugstore prints. They are more in the class of home-darkroom prints.</p>
        <p>You don't process them that way to save money, but to have as much control of the creative aspects of processing as you can.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Snapshots printed at home may be pricey, but I don't think computer-printed pictures should be compared in price with drugstore prints. They are more in the class of home-darkroom prints.</p>
        <p>You don't process them that way to save money, but to have as much control of the creative aspects of processing as you can.</p>
        <p>Home-darkroom printing is pricey, too. A sheet of 8-by-10 color print paper runs about $1 or more. The chemicals cost plenty. Then the first print is never right. The fourth or fifth, maybe.</p>
        <p>But with computer processing, you don't have those wasted ''test prints.'' Either way is pricey by mass-market standards, but if you're talking about photographic art, computer processing has much to commend it.</p>
        <p>JIM JONDROW  Tucson</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
